I used http://flint.cs.yale.edu/cs422/doc/ELF_Format.pdf.  It mentions 64-bit in some sections, so I'd assume it to call out bitness specific type sizes, and the section on the notes does not.

I'm also seeing these being 32-bit on my 64-bit host:

$ file /bin/ls
/bin/ls: ELF 64-bit LSB  executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked (uses shared libs), for GNU/Linux 2.6.24, BuildID[sha1]=8d0966ce81ec6609bbf4aa439c77138e2f48a471, stripped

$ readelf -x .note.gnu.build-id /bin/ls

Hex dump of section '.note.gnu.build-id':
  0x00400274 04000000 14000000 03000000 474e5500 ............GNU.
  0x00400284 8d0966ce 81ec6609 bbf4aa43 9c77138e ..f...f....C.w..
  0x00400294 2f48a471                            /H.q

